ANTHRAX - ARGENTINA: (BUENOS AIRES) BOVINE
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 8 Jan 2014
From: Ramon Noseda <rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar> [edited]


Bovine anthrax outbreak -- Partido of Mar Chiquita, Province of Buenos Aires
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A herd of 450 heifers, aged 15 months, on an estancia near to the Calfucura railway station in the partido (county) of Mar Chiquita has suffered 8 sudden deaths. They were grazing a natural pasture bordering Canal 7, opened in 1900, which drains floodwaters from the central zone of the province [Buenos Aires]. Over some 10 days the animals started to die suddenly. Metatarsal bones from the affected animals were submitted to the laboratory for analysis and showed mixed cultures of 40 percent _Bacillus anthracis_ and 60 percent _Escherichia coli_. They were sensitive to tetracycline, tilmicosin, gentamycin, florfenicol, and ciprofloxacin, and resistant to trimethoprim. None of the animals had been vaccinated against anthrax. There had been a prior anthrax outbreak in this pasture in 2007. The carcasses were burnt. All persons handling the carcasses wore suitable protective clothing and gloves.

The last outbreak of anthrax in Mar Chiquita was in January 2008 [see ProMED-mail 20080201.0400]. Mar Chiquita is in the Rural Control & Surveillance Program of Buenos Aires Province.

--
Dr Ramon Noseda
CFO-Director/Microbiologist
